bbr=on}}\n| Under construction\n| Grand Jamia Mosque, also known as Bahria Town Jamia Masjid Complex, is an under-construction [[Cultural center|cultural]] complex. When completed, the complex will include the world's third largest [[mosque]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/business/07-Jan-2015/groundbreaking-ceremony-of-grand-jamia-masjid|title=Groundbreaking ceremony|date=7 January 2015|work=The Nation|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/817839/bahria-breaks-ground-on-worlds-3rd-largest-mosque/|title=Bahria breaks ground on world's 3rd largest mosque|date=7 January 2015|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/Pakistan/253767-Karachi-Foundation-stone-of-worlds-3rd-largest-m|title=Karachi: Foundation stone of world's 3rd largest mosque laid  - Pakistan - Dunya News|work=dunyanews.tv|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Grand Mosque Allahabad]]\n| [[File:GMA Outside hall front view.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Naushahro Feroze District]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|10,000}}\n| {{convert|7400|m2|abbr=on}}\n| Under construction\n| Grand Mosque Allahabad is located in [[Kandiaro]], [[Sindh]].\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Mosque, Allahabad |url=http://www.islahulmuslimeen.org/grand-mosque-allahabad |website=www.islahulmuslimeen.org |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref> \n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Grand Jamia Mosque, Lahore]]\n| [[File:Grand_Jamia_Masjid_Bahria_Town_Lahore_Pakistan_cropped.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|100,000}}\n| \n| 2014\n| Seventh largest mosque in the world, and the largest in Pakistan in terms of surface area. It can accommodate 25,000 worshipers indoors, while the courtyard and corridor leading to the main halls of worship can accommodate a total of 70,000.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-10-12/news/54928831_1_mosque-multan-pakistan|title=Pakistan's third largest mosque,|work=timesofindia-economictimes|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/775536/unparalleled-achievement-zardari-inaugurates-pakistans-largest-mosque/|title=Unparalleled achievement: Zardari inaugurates Pakistan\u2019s largest mosque|date=15 October 2014|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beautifulmosque.com/grand-jamia-mosque-in-lahore-pakistan|title=Beautiful Mosque Pictures|website=www.beautifulmosque.com|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| Jamia Masjid Banbhore\n|[[File:Floor of the Jamia Masjid Banbhore dating back 727 AD.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Thatta]], [[Sindh]]\n| \n| \n| 727 AD\n| [[Banbhore]] is an ancient city dating to the 1st century BC located in [[Sindh]], Pakistan. The eastern part of the city contains ruins of Banbhore Mosque with an inscription dating to 727 AD, sixteen years after the conquest of Sindh, indicating the best-preserved example of the earliest mosques in the region. Ruins are still preserved in the city.\n|<ref name=Wesler>{{cite book|title=An Archaeology of Religion|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0761858454|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qSExw3tH1oC&pg=PA253|author=Kit W. Wesler|accessdate=8 September 2012|page=253|date=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Mosque of Banbhore|url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=14204|publisher=ArchNet|accessdate=8 September 2012|quote=... the Jami' Masjid of Banbhore is one of the earliest known mosques in the Indo-Pakistan subcontinent.}}</ref><ref name=Sindh>{{cite web|title=Banbhore Museum|url=http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|work=Culture Department|publisher=Govt. of Sindh|accessdate=3 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108165854/http://www.culture.gos.pk/index.php/govt-of-sindh-museums-galleries/banbhore-museum|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Mosque (Khudabad)]]\n|[[File:Main building of Jamia Masjid Khudabad.jpg|160px]]\n|[[Dadu District]], [[Sindh]]\n|{{nts|5000}}\n|\n|1700 - 1718\n| The mosque is situated in [[Khudabad]] in [[Dadu District]] and was built during the reign of [[Yar Muhammad Kalhoro]] between 1700 and 1718.\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamia Mosque (Khudabad) in Dadu District |url=https://www.sindhidunya.com/khudabad-mosque-antique-heritage-sindh/ |website=www.sindhidunya.com |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque|Jamia Al-Kauthar]]\n|[[File:Jamia Al Kauthar Mosque.png|160px]]\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|{{nts|2500}}\n|\n|1990\n|Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque is adjacent to the [[Shia]] [[seminary]] [[Alkauthar Islamic University|Al-Kauthar University]]. The iconic dome of this mosque is about 30 meters high from the ground level, and its 15 meters diameter makes the dome one of the largest in the country.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alkauthar.edu.pk/mosque/|title=Jamia Al-Kauthar Mosque}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Jamia Masjid Umar Farooq]]\n|\n| [[Godhra, Karachi]], [[New Karachi]], [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n|\n|\n| 1973\n|\n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Kuzkandi Jamiah Masjid]]\n| [[Image:kuzkandimasjid.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Baghdada]], [[Mardan]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| \n| \n| 1950s\n| \n|\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad|Lal Masjid]] <br />(Red Mosque)\n| [[Image:Red Mosque Islamabad 1.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| \n| \n| 1965\n| The Lal Masjid, also known as the Red Mosque, was built in 1965 and is named for its red walls and interiors. The mosque is one of the oldest mosques in Islamabad.\n|<ref name=\"bbc030707\">{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6503477.stm| title = Profile: Islamabad's Red Mosque| publisher = BBC | date=July 3, 2007 | accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1345068|title=The legacy of Lal Masjid|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Mohabbat Khan Mosque]]\n| [[File:MKmosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Peshawar]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{nts|14000}}\n| {{convert|2800|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1670s\n| Mohabbat Khan Mosque is a 17th-century [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]-era mosque in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]]. The mosque was built between 1660 and 1670, and named after the Mughal governor of [[Peshawar]], Nawab [[Ali Mardan Khan|Mahabat Khan bin Ali Mardan Khan]].\n| <ref>{{cite journal|title=Mahabat Khan Mosque|journal=Pharos:Research Journal of the Shaykh Zayed Islamic Centre|date=1996|volume=3|issue=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PK_XAAAAMAAJ&q=khan+mosque+peshawar&dq=khan+mosque+peshawar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGvJfi_6XWAhXCRSYKHcsGCDo4FBDoAQglMAA|accessdate=15 September 2017|publisher=University of Peshawar}}</ref><ref name=dawn>{{cite news|title=AROUND TOWN: Masjid Mahabat Khan: Splendour of Mughal art|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/432286|accessdate=15 September 2017|agency=Dawn|date=5 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com.pk/search?rlz=1C1CHBF_enPK777PK777&ei=VLhhW9XHKKfjsAeG6aiYAg&q=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&oq=Mahabat+Khan+Mosque+number+of+worshippers&gs_l=psy-ab.3..33i21k1.524.5689.0.5830.28.18.1.0.0.0.366.2052.2-3j4.7.0....0...1.1.64.psy-ab..21.3.847...0j0i22i30k1j33i22i29i30k1.0.byi8EhNzChQ#lpqa=d,2|title=What is the capacity of the prayers that can be accommodated by the mosque?|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n|[[Qasim Ali Khan Mosque]]\n|[[File:Qasim Ali Khan Mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Peshawar]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| \n| \n| \n| Qasim Ali Khan Mosque was built in 1842. There is a myth that the mosque was constructed during the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] era.\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1190142|title=Facts and fiction surrounding the historic Masjid Qasim Ali Khan|last=Shinwari|first=Sher Alam|date=2015-06-24|work=Dawn|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Moti Masjid (Lahore)|Moti Masjid]]\n| [[File:Moti Mosque (inside Lahore Fort).JPG|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| {{convert|160|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1635 \n| Moti Masjid is a 17th-century [[religious]] [[building]] located inside the [[Lahore Fort]]. It is a small, [[white marble]] structure built by [[Mughal Empire|Mughal emperor]] [[Jahangir]], and is among his prominent extensions to the Lahore Fort Complex.\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Dar|first1=Nadeem|title=A pearl inside Lahore Fort \u2013 Moti Masjid|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2015/06/20/a-pearl-inside-lahore-fort-moti-masjid/|accessdate=6 January 2017|agency=Pakistan Today|date=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=2607 Lahore Fort Complex: Moti Masjid] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525055009/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=2607 |date=25 May 2011 }} at ArchNet. Retrieved 16 April 2008.</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Neevin Mosque]]\n| [[File:Neevin Masjid 3 (WCLA).jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|100}}\n| \n| 1460\n|Located in [[Walled City of Lahore]], Neevin Mosque was built by [[Lodi dynasty]] under the rule of its first king [[Bahlul Lodi]].\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://defence.pk/pdf/threads/neevin-masjid-the-8th-wonder.418210/|title=Neevin Masjid \u2013 the 8th wonder|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=Dar>{{cite news|last1=Dar|first1=Nadeem|title=An architectural wonder, 25 feet under|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/architectural-wonder-25-feet-under/#.WFsF3KIrLBo|accessdate=21 December 2016|publisher=The News (Pakistan)|date=5 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=Qureishi>{{cite web|last1=Qureishi|first1=Tania|title=Neevin Masjid \u2013 the 8th wonder|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/blog/2016/01/16/neevin-masjid-the-8th-wonder/|publisher=Pakistan Today|accessdate=21 December 2016|date=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Oonchi Mosque]]\n| [[File:Unchi_Masjid_2_(WCLA).jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| \n| N.A.\n|[[Mughal Era]] mosque located along the Hakiman Bazaar, near the [[Bhati Gate]] which leads into the [[Walled City of Lahore]]. Unlike other mosques in the Walled City of Lahore, no inscription exists which signifies the year of the mosque's construction.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://walledcitylahore.gop.pk/oonchi-masjid-of-bhatti-gate-another-wonder-lost-with-the-passage-of-time/|title=OONCHI MASJID OF BHATTI GATE \u2014 ANOTHER WONDER LOST WITH THE PASSAGE OF TIME|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Shah Jahan Mosque, Thatta|Shah Jahan Mosque]]\n| [[Image:Shah Jahan Mosque Center (20673302596).jpg|160px]]\n| [[Thatta]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|20000}}\n| {{convert|3050|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1647\n| Shah Jahan Mosque is a 17th-century building that serves as the [[Jama Masjid|central mosque]] for the city of [[Thatta]], Sindh. It was built during the reign of [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Shah Jahan]].\n| <ref>{{cite book|last1=Sluglett|first1=Peter|title=Atlas of Islamic History|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317588979}}</ref><ref name=asher>{{cite book|last1=Asher|first1=Catherine|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|date=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521267281|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA349&dq=shah+jahan+thatta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq5L2T6Y7VAhWF7CYKHR3zA5YQ6AEIMjAC#v=snippet&q=thatta&f=false|accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discover-pakistan.com/shah-jahan-mosque.html|title=SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SHAH JAHAN MOSQUE\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://visitpak.com/shah-jahan-mosque-or-shahjahani-mosque-thatta-sindh/|title=Shah Jahan Mosque, Thatta|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Shahi Eid Gah Mosque]]\n| [[File:Eidgah_mosque.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Multan]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| \n| {{convert|1250|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1735\n| Located on the main Multan-Lahore highway in the Northeast the city, the mosque is adjacent to the 20th century [[Sufi]] shrine of [[Ahmad Saeed Kazmi]].\n| <ref>{{cite book|last1=Yousaf|first1=Mohammad|title=A Brief History of Multan|date=1971|publisher=Ferozsons}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Shahi Mosque, Chitral]]\n| [[File:Shahi Mosque, Chitral.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Chitral]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{nts|20000}}\n| \n| 1924\n| It was the principal [[mosque]] of Chitral at the time of the existence of the [[Chitral (princely state)|State of Chitral]]. The mosque was built by [[Shuja ul-Mulk]] in 1924.\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Shahi Mosque, Chitral |url=https://www.croozi.com/shahi-masjid-chitral-kpk-pakistan |website=www.croozi.com |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Information on alamy.com |url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-shahi-masjid-chitral-built-in-1924-by-shujah-ul-mulk-then-the-mehta-116959865.html |website=www.alamy.com |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Built in 1924\">{{cite web|title=Built in 1924 by Shuja ul Mulk|url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-shahi-masjid-chitral-built-in-1924-by-shujah-ul-mulk-then-the-mehta-116959865.html|website=www.alamy.com|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mehtar of Chitral from 1895 to 1936 |url=http://www.dilkashpakistan.com/shahi-masjid-chitral-beautiful-pakistan/ |website=www.dilkashpakistan.com |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Sunehri Mosque, Lahore|Sunehri Mosque]]\n| [[File:Sunehri masjid top view 2.JPG|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|5000}}\n| {{convert|25948|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1753\n| Sunehri Mosque is located in the Kashmiri Bazaar of the [[Walled City of Lahore]]. The mosque was built in 1753 when the [[Mughal Empire]] was in decline.\n| <ref name=\"Sonehri Mosque\">{{cite news|title=Sonehri Mosque|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/mosque_sonehri.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|agency=Lahore Sites}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/mosque_sonehri.html|title=Sonehri Mosque|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Masjid e Tooba|Tooba Mosque]]\n|[[File:Tooba Mosque-44.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]\n| {{nts|5000}}\n| {{convert|3280|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1969\n| Masjid-e-Tooba was built in 1969 in [[Defence Housing Society, Karachi|Defence Housing Society]], Karachi. It is often claimed to be the largest single-dome mosque in the world.\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhatoday.com/masjid-e-tooba-all-you-need-to-know/|title=Masjid-e-Tooba \u2013 All You Need To Know!|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discover-pakistan.com/masjid-e-tooba.html|title=MASJID-E-TOOBA|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"center\"\n| [[Wazir Khan Mosque]]\n| [[File:Wazir Khan Mosque by Moiz.jpg|160px]]\n| [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| {{nts|10000}}\n| {{convert|3825|m2|abbr=on}}\n| 1642\n| The mosque was commissioned during the reign of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] Emperor [[Shah Jahan]]. Construction of Wazir Khan Mosque began in 1634 [[Common era|C.E.]] and was completed in 1641.\n| <ref>{{cite news|title=Conservation of the Wazir Khan Mosque Lahore: Preliminary Report on Condition and Risk Assessment|url=http://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/6585/original/DPC3347.pdf?1384798179|accessdate=25 August 2016|agency=Aga Khan Development Network|date=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827000354/http://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/6585/original/DPC3347.pdf?1384798179|archive-date=27 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{cite web|title=Wazir Khan's Mosque, Lahore|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1278/|publisher=UNESCO| 